{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9921b3d4-2790-415e-b659-7a5cff1da71f","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** — it's lightweight and doesn't require `perf` or `root`:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (default ~30s, Ctrl+C to stop)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- Copy the trace out: `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`\n- If you need a format for Speedscope: add `--format speedscope`\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, grab the standalone build from the [dotnet-diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics).\n\nFor deeper native + managed analysis, use `dotnet-trace` with `--profile cpu-sampling` combined with `--clrevents` — but for most high-CPU investigations, the default CPU sampling profile is sufficient.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8b9c30fa-33dc-4f28-a6d4-b4ac60003fd4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":363,"requestId":"6088:C5472:24D8D9:304E53:69FFDFE2"},"id":"0d39be32-4623-4ffa-9d12-89c897f6c9b7","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:31:23.400Z","parentId":"1c09c160-b1e6-41cd-844f-d807f92b787a"}
